%S A392439 13,19,31,37,41,43,61,67,73,79,97,101,103,109,113,127,139,151,157,163,
%T A392439 181,193,197,199,211,223,229,241,271,277,281,283,307,313,331,337,349,
%U A392439 353,367,373,379,397,401,409,421,433,439,449,457,461,463,487,491,499,521
%N A392439 Prime numbers p whose predecessor k = (p - 1) is a composable number (A392440).
%C A392439 Numbers k are defined as composable or p-composable if k/p is a sum of nontrivial divisors, where p is the smallest prime divisor of k. Since any p-composable number with p greater than 2 is odd, and the predecessor of any odd prime is even, only 2-composable numbers can precede primes.
%C A392439 A prime p, where k = p - 1 is 2-composable, can be expressed as p = 1 + Sum(S) + k/2. Here, S is a subset of k's divisors strictly between 1 and k/2 that sums to k/2. Including k/2 in S produces a subset of divisors of k less than k that sums to k, thereby proving that k is semiperfect.
%C A392439 Among the 9592 primes less than 10^5, 6043 are preceded by a composable number. Therefore, approximately 63% of the primes in this range possess such a sum representation.
%H A392439 Peter Luschny, <a href="https://github.com/PeterLuschny/Gists/blob/main/ComposableRigidSparse.ipynb">Composable, rigid, and sparse numbers</a>. A Python notebook.
%e A392439 13 is a composable-preceded prime. Its predecessor is 12 and since the nontrivial divisors 2 and 4 of 12 sum to 12/2, we can write the prime as 13 = 1 + (2 + 4) + 6.
%e A392439 .
%e A392439   p    | Witness of composable-preceded prime
%e A392439   -------------------------------------------
%e A392439   13   | 1 +  2 +  4 +  6
%e A392439   19   | 1 +  3 +  6 +  9
%e A392439   31   | 1 +  5 + 10 + 15
%e A392439   37   | 1 +  6 + 12 + 18
%e A392439   41   | 1 +  2 +  8 + 10 + 20
%e A392439   43   | 1 +  7 + 14 + 21
%e A392439   61   | 1 + 10 + 20 + 30
%e A392439   67   | 1 + 11 + 22 + 33
%e A392439   73   | 1 + 12 + 24 + 36
%e A392439   79   | 1 + 13 + 26 + 39
%e A392439   97   | 1 + 16 + 32 + 48
%e A392439   101  | 1 +  5 + 20 + 25 + 50
%o A392439 (Python)  # Function 'is_composable' is defined in A392440 (see also links).
%o A392439 from sympy import sieve
%o A392439 def A392439_list(upto: int) -> list[int]:
%o A392439     primes = []
%o A392439     for p in sieve.primerange(2, upto + 1):
%o A392439         if is_composable(p - 1):
%o A392439             primes.append(p)
%o A392439     return primes
%o A392439 print(A392439_list(522))
%Y A392439 Cf. A000040, A392440 (composable), A392438 (2-composable), A005835 (semiperfect), A032741 (proper divisors), A070824 (nontrivial divisors).
